SIMPLE: unhinge
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Unhinge
<hw>Un*hinge"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[1st pref.
<ets>un-</ets> + <ets>hinge</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To take from the hinges; <as>as, to <ex>unhinge</ex>
a door</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To displace; to unfix by violence.</def>
<rj><au>Blackmore.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To render unstable or wavering; to unsettle; <as>as,
to <ex>unhinge</ex> one's mind or opinions; to <ex>unhinge</ex> the
nerves</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why should I then <qex>unhinge</qex> my brains, ruin my mind?</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His sufferings, nay the revolutions of his fate, had not in the
least <qex>unhinged</qex> his mind.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Unhingement</ent>⟦br⟧
